Exercise 1 - Descriptive statistics

We will be working on data from a randomised trial of two treatment regimens for lung cancer, the Veteran’s Administration Lunc Cancer study. The data are provided as part of the survival-package and can be loaded by first installing the package (NB if you have already installed the package, you don’t have to do it again):

install.packages("survival")

Load the data into an R-data set with the name vet using:

vet <- survival::veteran

The data set vet contains the following variables:

  • trt: 1=standard 2=test
  • celltype: 1=squamous, 2=smallcell, 3=adeno, 4=large
  • time: survival time
  • status: censoring status, 1=dead, 0=censored
  • karno: Karnofsky performance score (100=good)
  • diagtime: months from diagnosis to randomisation
  • age: in years
  • prior: prior therapy 0=no, 10=yes

Data manipulations and simple descriptive statistics

6. Define a dummy(0/1)-variable named karno50 in the data set indicating whether the Karnofsky score is above(\(\geq\)) or below(<) 50 points. Hint: You may use the ifelse()-function (see e.g. Chapter 5.4.3 of the online introduction to R).
Show the solution for 6 
vet$karno50 <- ifelse(vet$karno >= 50, 1, 0)
7. How many of the veterans with a Karnofsky score below, respectively above, 50 points died (status==1)? Find out in two ways:
  1. By defining subsets of the data containing only the dead veterans with a Karnofsky score above, respectively below, 50 points. Count the number of veterans in each sub data set.
Show the solution for 7.1 
vet1 <- subset(vet, status==1 & karno50==1)
dim(vet1)
## [1] 91  9
vet2 <- subset(vet, status==1 & karno50==0)
dim(vet2)
## [1] 37  9
  1. By making a two-way table of status vs karno50.
Show the solution for 7.2 
tab <- table(vet$karno50, vet$status, dnn = c("Karno > 50", "Status"))
8. Determine the proportion of dead veterans for those with a Karnofsky score below, respectively above, 50 points.

12. Make a Table 1 including the variables celltype, karno, diagtime, age, prior stratified on treatment trt. Make sure that all variables are tabulated in the correct way. Does it make sense to report mean and SD for all the quantitative variables or should we rather use median and IQR (Inter Quartile Range) (if so, use the help function to find out how) (hint: print(object, showAllLevels=T, nonnormal = c('age','diagtime')))?
Show the solution for 12 
library(tableone)
vet1 <- subset(vet, select = c(celltype, karno, diagtime, age, prior, trt))
tab1 <- CreateTableOne(data = vet1, strata = 'trt', test = FALSE,
                       vars = c('celltype', 'karno', 'diagtime', 'age', 'prior'),
                       factorVars = c('prior'))
print(tab1, showAllLevels = T, nonnormal = c('age','diagtime'))

10. Create another scatterplot of carapace width versus rear width. Change the default axis labels to make them understandable to the reader (e.g.~spell out the variable names abbreviated in the data)
Show the solution for 10 
plot(crabs$CW, crabs$RW, xlab = "Carapace width", ylab = "Rear width")

11. Use separate plot characters for each sex (hint: change to a numeric variable)
Show the solution for 11 
plot(crabs$CW, crabs$RW, xlab = "Carapace width", ylab = "Rear width",
     pch = as.numeric(crabs$sex))

12. Color the data points according to the species type
Show the solution for 12 
plot(crabs$CW, crabs$RW, xlab = "Carapace width", ylab = "Rear width",
     pch = as.numeric(crabs$sex), col = crabs$sp)

13. Add a legend to the plot to illustrate how sex and species type are specified in the plot.
Show the solution for 13 
plot(crabs$CW, crabs$RW, xlab = "Carapace width", ylab = "Rear width",
     pch = as.numeric(crabs$sex), col = crabs$sp)
legend('topleft',c('Female, B','Male B','Female O','Male O'),
       pch = c(1, 2, 1, 2), col = c(1, 1, 2, 2))

14. Add a title to the plot
Show the solution for 14 
plot(crabs$CW, crabs$RW, xlab = "Carapace width", ylab = "Rear width",
     pch = as.numeric(crabs$sex), col = crabs$sp,
     main = 'Rear width vs. carapace width')
legend('topleft', c('Female, B','Male B','Female O','Male O'),
       pch = c(1, 2, 1, 2), col = c(1, 1, 2, 2))

15. What information can be derived from the plot? Do you see any patterns?
Show the solution for 15 
"In the plot we can see that there is a linear relationship between the variables carapace width and rear width. We can also see that the rear width of the males is lower than the one of the females for carapace width greater than 30 and this difference becomes bigger for increasing values of carapace width. From the plot we cannot identify any difference among the species for rear width and carapace width."

From the plot we cannot identify any difference among the species for rear width and carapace width."

y <- c(1:10)
3. Plot \(y\) versus \(x\) without axes. Increase the font size of the axis labels. Change the box type so that it only appears at the bottom and to the left
Show the solution for 3 
plot(x, y, cex.lab = 2, bty = 'l')

4. Make the \(y\)-axis label horizontal
Show the solution for 4 
plot(x, y, cex.lab = 2, bty = 'l', las = 1)

Show the solution for 5 
plot(x, y, cex.lab = 2, bty = 'l', las = 1)

Show the solution for 6 
plot(x, y, cex.lab = 2, bty = 'l', las = 1)

Bonus exercises

Sorting data (OPTIONAL)

Reload the veteran study data:

Show the solution for 1 
vet <- survival::veteran
1. Order the data vet by increasing value of the time-variable.
Show the solution for 1 
vet <- vet[order(vet$time), ]
2. Order the data by decreasing value of status variable (i.e. the dead first) and increasing value of time.
Show the solution for 2 
vet <- vet[order(-vet$status, vet$time), ]
3. Suppose we want to add data on one more veteran to our vet data set. The veteran has values
new <- data.frame(trt = 1,
                  celltype = "large",
                  time = 204,
                  status = 0,
                  karno = 88,
                  age = 55)

Add the values for this extra veteran to the vet data using rbind(). R will give you an error message - what is the problem and how can you correct the error?

Show the solution for 3 
new$id <- 138
new$karno50 <- ifelse(new$karno >= 50, 1, 0)
